VPC Peering in AWS allows you to connect two Virtual Private Clouds (VPCs) privately — as if they were part of the same network — without using public internet routes. It’s ideal for secure communication between environments (like dev ↔ prod, or cross-account setups).

🔗 Core Concept
A VPC Peering Connection is a network link between two VPCs that enables traffic routing using private IPs.

Works across same or different AWS accounts.

Can be intra-region or inter-region (between different AWS regions).

Uses private IP addressing — no need for VPN or public endpoints.

🧩 Key Components
Component	        Description	                                                                    Example
Requester VPC	The VPC initiating the peering request.	                                          VPC-A (10.0.0.0/16)
Accepter VPC	The VPC receiving and accepting the request.	                                  VPC-B (192.168.0.0/16)
Route Tables	Must be updated in both VPCs to route traffic through the peering connection.	  Add route to peer CIDR
DNS Resolution	Optional — can enable private DNS resolution across peered VPCs.	              Useful for internal services
⚙️ How It Works (Step-by-Step)
Create Peering Connection

From VPC console → “Peering Connections” → “Create Peering Connection.”

Specify requester and accepter VPCs.

Accept the Request

The accepter VPC owner must approve the connection.

Update Route Tables

Add routes in both VPCs pointing to the peer’s CIDR via the peering connection.

Modify Security Groups

Allow inbound/outbound traffic from the peer’s CIDR range.

Test Connectivity

Ping or SSH between instances using private IPs.

🚫 Limitations
No transitive peering → VPC-A ↔ VPC-B ↔ VPC-C doesn’t automatically connect all three.

Overlapping CIDR blocks → Peering not allowed.

No edge-to-edge routing → Can’t route traffic to internet gateways, VPNs, or NATs through a peer.

Manual route updates → No automatic propagation.

🧠 Best Practices
Plan non-overlapping CIDR ranges early.

Use tags to track peering connections.

Enable DNS resolution for smoother internal communication.

Use AWS Transit Gateway for complex multi-VPC topologies.

Regularly audit route tables and SGs for consistency.

✅ In short: VPC Peering is a simple, cost-effective way to connect private networks securely — perfect for internal communication between environments or accounts.
